  "author_association": "MEMBER",
  "body": "We allow users to specify `LoadBalancerIP` in the Service object. If the user later removes this from the Service Spec, the controller will fail to sync.\r\n \r\nFor example:\r\n1. Controller creates an LB for Service.Spec.LoadBalancerIP = \"1.1.1.1\" with a user-owned static IP address.\r\n2. User updates the Service to remove the requested LoadBalancerIP\r\n3. Controller tries to [ensure the IP](https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/blob/v1.8.0-alpha.3/pkg/cloudprovider/providers/gce/gce_loadbalancer_external.go#L886-L915) used by the existing forwarding rule (i.e., \"1.1.1.1\"). It encounters a conflict. Controller assumes it owns the IP and [tries to get the Address](https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/blob/v1.8.0-alpha.3/pkg/cloudprovider/providers/gce/gce_loadbalancer_external.go#L909) by name but fails.\r\n\r\nWe can fix the controller to continue syncing and using the user-owned IP for the LB, or create a new address for the LB. The former seems less disruptive to me, but the downside is that if user will not be able to let other components use this IP (i.e., 1.1.1.1) unless they explicitly delete the Service. I think it's ok but would like more opinions.\r\n\r\n@bowei @nicksardo thoughts? ",
